      "content": "Many contemporary critiques argue that the primary function of the supply-side argument in modern policy discussions is political framing rather than rigorous economic forecasting. While the original theoretical underpinnings—that incentives drive productive behavior—retain some merit, their application to wealth redistribution often overlooks distributional consequences. Therefore, you can accurately frame them as intellectually consistent in one narrow sense but politically convenient when advocating for wealth concentration.",
